Q.1 Payment Card Data and Regulatory Standards [15M]
(a) What is Payment Card Data Security Standards (PCI DSS)
Answer:
•	PCI DSS stands for Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard.
•	It is a global security standard created by major card brands (Visa, MasterCard, American Express, etc.) to protect cardholder data.
•	Purpose:
•	Prevent data breaches and theft of credit/debit card information.
•	Ensure secure storage, transmission, and processing of cardholder data.
Key Requirements of PCI DSS:
1.	Install and maintain firewalls to protect cardholder data.
2.	Do not use default passwords and security settings.
3.	Protect stored cardholder data (e.g., encryption).
4.	Encrypt transmission of cardholder data over open networks.
5.	Use antivirus and malware protection.
6.	Maintain secure systems and applications.
7.	Restrict access to cardholder data to authorized personnel only.
8.	Track and monitor all access to network resources.
9.	Regularly test security systems and processes.
10.	Maintain an information security policy.
________________________________________
(b) What is RBI PSS (Reserve Bank of India – Payment and Settlement Systems)
Answer:
•	RBI PSS refers to Payment and Settlement Systems regulated by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI).
•	Objective:
•	Ensure safe, secure, and efficient payments and settlements in India.
•	Provide legal, regulatory, and operational framework for all payment systems.
Components of PSS:
1.	RTGS (Real Time Gross Settlement): Large-value interbank payments in real-time.
2.	NEFT (National Electronic Funds Transfer): Electronic transfer of funds between banks.
3.	Retail Payment Systems: Card payments, UPI, e-wallets.
4.	Settlement Systems: Netting and clearing of payments between financial institutions.
Importance:
•	Reduces fraud risk.
•	Improves efficiency of financial transactions.
•	Ensures consumer protection.
________________________________________
(c) What is PCI Compliance Checklist
Answer:
•	PCI Compliance Checklist is a structured guide to ensure an organization meets PCI DSS requirements.
Typical Checklist Items:
1.	Network Security: Firewalls and secure configuration.
2.	Cardholder Data Protection: Encryption of stored and transmitted data.
3.	Access Control: Restrict access to authorized personnel only.
4.	Monitoring and Logging: Track access and maintain audit logs.
5.	Security Policies: Regular updates and employee training.
6.	Regular Testing: Vulnerability scans and penetration tests.
7.	Incident Response: Preparedness for potential breaches.
